Download Materials

assertr

The purpose of this document is to go over the package assertr, a package that is useful in testing out assumptions about a dataset before undertaking data analysis.

# install.packages("assertr")
library(assertr)

assertr functions

The main functions from the assertr functions are - assert: takes a data frame, a predicate function, and an arbitrary number of columns to apply the predicate function to. The predicate function (a function that returns a logical/boolean value) is then applied to every element of the columns selected, and will raise an error if it finds any violations. Internally, the assert function uses dplyr’s select function to extract the columns to test the predicate function on.

  • verify: takes a data frame (its first argument is provided by the %>% operator above), and a logical (boolean) expression. Then, verify evaluates that expression using the scope of the provided data frame. If any of the logical values of the expression’s result are FALSE, verify will raise an error that terminates any further processing of the pipeline.

  • insist: takes a data frame, a predicate-generating function, and an arbitrary number of columns. For each column, the the predicate-generating function is applied, returning a predicate. The predicate is then applied to every element of the columns selected, and will raise an error if it finds any violations. The reason for using a predicate-generating function to return a predicate to use against each value in each of the selected rows is so that, for example, bounds can be dynamically generated based on what the data look like; this the only way to, say, create bounds that check if each datum is within x z-scores, since the standard deviation isn’t known a priori. Internally, the insist function uses dplyr’s select function to extract the columns to test the predicate function on.

  • assert_rows: takes a data frame, a row reduction function, a predicate function, and an arbitrary number of columns to apply the predicate function to. The row reduction function is applied to the data frame, and returns a value for each row. The predicate function is then applied to every element of vector returned from the row reduction function, and will raise an error if it finds any violations. This functionality is useful, for example, in conjunction with the num_row_NAs() function to ensure that there is below a certain number of missing values in each row. Internally, the assert_rows function uses dplyr’sselect function to extract the columns to test the predicate function on.

  • insist_rows: takes a data frame, a row reduction function, a predicate-generating function, and an arbitrary number of columns to apply the predicate function to. The row reduction function is applied to the data frame, and returns a value for each row. The predicate-generating function is then applied to the vector returned from the row reduction function and the resultant predicate is applied to each element of that vector. It will raise an error if it finds any violations. This functionality is useful, for example, in conjunction with the maha_dist() function to ensure that there are no flagrant outliers. Internally, the assert_rows function uses dplyr’sselect function to extract the columns to test the predicate function on.

These functions are meant to be used after data has been loaded, but before analysis begins.

assertr also offers four (so far) predicate functions designed to be used with the assert and assert_rows functions:

  • not_na - that checks if an element is not NA
  • within_bounds - that returns a predicate function that checks if a numeric value falls within the bounds supplied
  • in_set - that returns a predicate function that checks if an element is a member of the set supplied. (also allows inverse for “not in set”)
  • is_uniq - that checks to see if each element appears only once

and predicate generators designed to be used with the insist and insist_rows functions:

  • within_n_sds - used to dynamically create bounds to check vector elements with based on standard z-scores
  • within_n_mads - better method for dynamically creating bounds to check vector elements with based on ‘robust’ z-scores (using median absolute deviation)

and the following row reduction functions designed to be used with assert_rows and insist_rows:

  • num_row_NAs - counts number of missing values in each row
  • maha_dist - computes the mahalanobis distance of each row (for outlier detection). It will coerce categorical variables into numerics if it needs to.
  • col_concat - concatenates all rows into strings
  • duplicated_across_cols - checking if a row contains a duplicated value across columns

and, finally, some other utilities for use with verify

  • has_all_names - check if the data frame or list has all supplied names
  • has_only_names - check that a data frame or list have only the names requested
  • has_class - checks if passed data has a particular class

Examples

We will now start to walkthrough how all of these functions are used in a pipeline/workflow. We will look at the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey Data (NHANES)

#install.packages("NHANES")
library(NHANES)
library(tidyverse)
## -- Attaching packages --------------------------------------- tidyverse 1.3.1 --
## v ggplot2 3.3.5     v purrr   0.3.4
## v tibble  3.1.6     v dplyr   1.0.7
## v tidyr   1.1.3     v stringr 1.4.0
## v readr   1.4.0     v forcats 0.5.1
## -- Conflicts ------------------------------------------ tidyverse_conflicts() --
## x dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
## x dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
nh <- NHANES

# Going to mess it up a bit for our purposes
set.seed(1234)
nh$Pulse[is.na(nh$Pulse)] <-  runif(sum(is.na(nh$Pulse)), min = -.1, max = 100)
nh %>% summarize(range(Pulse, na.rm = TRUE))
## # A tibble: 2 x 1
##   `range(Pulse, na.rm = TRUE)`
##                          <dbl>
## 1                      -0.0658
## 2                     136

Let us take the first step to ensure that we have all positive numbers for Pulse since it does not make sense for a pulse rate to be negative. To do this, we will use a simple call to verify.

nh %>%
  verify(Pulse > 0)  %>%
  summarise(range(Pulse, na.rm= TRUE))
## verification [Pulse > 0] failed! (3 failures)
## 
##     verb redux_fn predicate column index value
## 1 verify       NA Pulse > 0     NA  3311    NA
## 2 verify       NA Pulse > 0     NA  5208    NA
## 3 verify       NA Pulse > 0     NA  5422    NA
## Error: assertr stopped execution
nh %>% filter(Pulse <= 0) %>% select(Pulse)
## # A tibble: 3 x 1
##     Pulse
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0387
## 2 -0.0136
## 3 -0.0658

This stops the execution of the summarize function because negative numbers were found. The verify function takes a dataframe and a boolean as it’s input, while the assert function takes a dataframe, a predicate function, and some number of columns as input. assert uses the select function, which allows us to go through multiple columns at once.

# The within_bounds functions ensures that values are within a specified range. I'll check to make sure Age and BMI are between 0 and 50
#?within_bounds

nh %>%
  assert(within_bounds(0, 50), Age, BMI) %>% 
  summarise(range(Pulse, na.rm= TRUE))
## Column 'Age' violates assertion 'within_bounds(0, 50)' 2972 times
##     verb redux_fn            predicate column index value
## 1 assert       NA within_bounds(0, 50)    Age    11    66
## 2 assert       NA within_bounds(0, 50)    Age    12    58
## 3 assert       NA within_bounds(0, 50)    Age    13    54
## 4 assert       NA within_bounds(0, 50)    Age    15    58
## 5 assert       NA within_bounds(0, 50)    Age    19    60
##   [omitted 2967 rows]
## 
## 
## Column 'BMI' violates assertion 'within_bounds(0, 50)' 62 times
##     verb redux_fn            predicate column index value
## 1 assert       NA within_bounds(0, 50)    BMI   207 51.33
## 2 assert       NA within_bounds(0, 50)    BMI   345 81.25
## 3 assert       NA within_bounds(0, 50)    BMI   346 81.25
## 4 assert       NA within_bounds(0, 50)    BMI   363 52.08
## 5 assert       NA within_bounds(0, 50)    BMI   558 51.54
##   [omitted 57 rows]
## Error: assertr stopped execution

Did not work because some cases had BMI > 50 and/or Age > 50, so I will need to either take care of this or change my assertion.

As a note, verify takes an expression while assert takes a predicate and a column. "This might make the verify function look more elegant–but there’s an important drawback. verify has to evaluate the entire expression first, and then check if there were any violations. Because of this, verify can’t tell you the offending datum.

One important drawback to assert, and a consequence of its application of the predicate to columns, is that assert can’t confirm assertions about the data structure itself."

assert

Again, here are the built-in predicates for use with assert

  • not_na - that checks if an element is not NA
  • within_bounds - that returns a predicate function that checks if a numeric value falls within the bounds supplied
  • in_set - that returns a predicate function that checks if an element is a member of the set supplied. (also allows inverse for “not in set”)
  • is_uniq - that checks to see if each element appears only once

Using these predicates we can look in the nh dataset for a number of different conditions. - I want to make sure I have no NAs under ID - I want to ensure that my Age is from 0 - 80 - I want to ensure that the SmokeNow and HardDrugs columns are “Yes” or “No” answers only. - I want to ensure that each row has a unique Identifier (ID)

nh %>% 
  assert(not_na, ID) %>%  ## Passes no missing under ID
  assert(within_bounds(0, 80), Age) %>% 
  assert(in_set(c("No", "Yes")), SmokeNow, HardDrugs) %>% 
  assert(is_uniq, ID)
## Column 'ID' violates assertion 'is_uniq' 5354 times
##     verb redux_fn predicate column index value
## 1 assert       NA   is_uniq     ID     1 51624
## 2 assert       NA   is_uniq     ID     2 51624
## 3 assert       NA   is_uniq     ID     3 51624
## 4 assert       NA   is_uniq     ID     8 51647
## 5 assert       NA   is_uniq     ID     9 51647
##   [omitted 5349 rows]
## Error: assertr stopped execution

This pipeline works until you reach the is_uniq function, because the ID function is not unique since a patient can show up multiple times.

Custom Predicates

We are not limited to these four predicates, but we can create our own. You can either create an inline function or a function that you saved earlier and want to use multiple times.

Let’s say we have a column that we need to be either 4 characters long or 6 characters long, but nothing else. We could create own function:

char.4.6 <- function(x) if(nchar(x) == 4 | nchar(x) == 6) return(TRUE)

And then we can use it on our data

nh %>% 
  mutate(Gender = as.character(Gender)) %>% 
  assert(char.4.6, Gender)
## # A tibble: 10,000 x 76
##       ID SurveyYr Gender   Age AgeDecade AgeMonths Race1 Race3 Education   
##    <int> <fct>    <chr>  <int> <fct>         <int> <fct> <fct> <fct>       
##  1 51624 2009_10  male      34 " 30-39"        409 White <NA>  High School 
##  2 51624 2009_10  male      34 " 30-39"        409 White <NA>  High School 
##  3 51624 2009_10  male      34 " 30-39"        409 White <NA>  High School 
##  4 51625 2009_10  male       4 " 0-9"           49 Other <NA>  <NA>        
##  5 51630 2009_10  female    49 " 40-49"        596 White <NA>  Some College
##  6 51638 2009_10  male       9 " 0-9"          115 White <NA>  <NA>        
##  7 51646 2009_10  male       8 " 0-9"          101 White <NA>  <NA>        
##  8 51647 2009_10  female    45 " 40-49"        541 White <NA>  College Grad
##  9 51647 2009_10  female    45 " 40-49"        541 White <NA>  College Grad
## 10 51647 2009_10  female    45 " 40-49"        541 White <NA>  College Grad
## # ... with 9,990 more rows, and 67 more variables: MaritalStatus <fct>,
## #   HHIncome <fct>, HHIncomeMid <int>, Poverty <dbl>, HomeRooms <int>,
## #   HomeOwn <fct>, Work <fct>, Weight <dbl>, Length <dbl>, HeadCirc <dbl>,
## #   Height <dbl>, BMI <dbl>, BMICatUnder20yrs <fct>, BMI_WHO <fct>,
## #   Pulse <dbl>, BPSysAve <int>, BPDiaAve <int>, BPSys1 <int>, BPDia1 <int>,
## #   BPSys2 <int>, BPDia2 <int>, BPSys3 <int>, BPDia3 <int>, Testosterone <dbl>,
## #   DirectChol <dbl>, TotChol <dbl>, UrineVol1 <int>, UrineFlow1 <dbl>, ...

That passed perfectly because our Gender column has only male or female (4 or 6 characters). Let us try the equivalent function as an inline version.

nh %>% 
  mutate(Race1 = as.character(Race1)) %>% 
  assert(function(x) (nchar(x) == 4 | nchar(x) == 6), Race1)
## Column 'Race1' violates assertion 'function(x) (nchar(x) == 4 | nchar(x) == 6)' 10000 times
##     verb redux_fn                                   predicate column index
## 1 assert       NA function(x) (nchar(x) == 4 | nchar(x) == 6)  Race1     1
## 2 assert       NA function(x) (nchar(x) == 4 | nchar(x) == 6)  Race1     2
## 3 assert       NA function(x) (nchar(x) == 4 | nchar(x) == 6)  Race1     3
## 4 assert       NA function(x) (nchar(x) == 4 | nchar(x) == 6)  Race1     4
## 5 assert       NA function(x) (nchar(x) == 4 | nchar(x) == 6)  Race1     5
##   value
## 1 White
## 2 White
## 3 White
## 4 Other
## 5 White
##   [omitted 9995 rows]
## Error: assertr stopped execution

An error is caught here because most of the Race1 variable is not 4 or 6 characters.

insist

"Very often, there is a need to dynamically determine the predicate function to be used based on the vector being checked.

For example, to check to see if every element of a vector is within n standard deviations of the mean, you need to create a within_bounds predicate after dynamically determining the bounds by reading and computing on the vector itself.

To this end, the assert function is no good; it just applies a raw predicate to a vector. We need a function like assert that will apply predicate generators to vectors, return predicates, and then perform assert-like functionality by checking each element of the vectors with its respective custom predicate. This is precisely what insist does.

This is all much simpler than it may sound. Hopefully, the examples will clear up any confusion.

The primary use case for insist is in conjunction with the within_n_sds or within_n_mads predicate generator.

Suppose we wanted to check that every mpg value in the mtcars data set was within 3 standard deviations of the mean before finding the average miles per gallon for each number of engine cylinders. We could write something like this:"

nh %>% 
  insist(within_n_sds(3), BPSysAve)
## Column 'BPSysAve' violates assertion 'within_n_sds(3)' 109 times
##     verb redux_fn       predicate   column index value
## 1 insist       NA within_n_sds(3) BPSysAve    90   172
## 2 insist       NA within_n_sds(3) BPSysAve    91   172
## 3 insist       NA within_n_sds(3) BPSysAve   116   174
## 4 insist       NA within_n_sds(3) BPSysAve   142   181
## 5 insist       NA within_n_sds(3) BPSysAve   144   191
##   [omitted 104 rows]
## Error: assertr stopped execution
nh %>% 
  insist(within_n_sds(2), BPSysAve)
## Column 'BPSysAve' violates assertion 'within_n_sds(2)' 357 times
##     verb redux_fn       predicate   column index value
## 1 insist       NA within_n_sds(2) BPSysAve    54   156
## 2 insist       NA within_n_sds(2) BPSysAve    90   172
## 3 insist       NA within_n_sds(2) BPSysAve    91   172
## 4 insist       NA within_n_sds(2) BPSysAve   116   174
## 5 insist       NA within_n_sds(2) BPSysAve   128    80
##   [omitted 352 rows]
## Error: assertr stopped execution

“After the predicate generator, insist takes an arbitrary number of columns just like assert using the syntax of dplyr’s select function. If you wanted to check that everything in mtcars is within 10 standard deviations of the mean (of each column vector), you can do so like this:”

nh %>% 
  select_if(is.numeric) %>% 
  insist(within_n_sds(10), Age:SmokeAge)
## Column 'UrineFlow1' violates assertion 'within_n_sds(10)' 3 times
##     verb redux_fn        predicate     column index  value
## 1 insist       NA within_n_sds(10) UrineFlow1  3416 12.346
## 2 insist       NA within_n_sds(10) UrineFlow1  8542 11.069
## 3 insist       NA within_n_sds(10) UrineFlow1  8915 17.167
## 
## Column 'UrineFlow2' violates assertion 'within_n_sds(10)' 1 time
##     verb redux_fn        predicate     column index  value
## 1 insist       NA within_n_sds(10) UrineFlow2  1745 13.692
## 
## Column 'nPregnancies' violates assertion 'within_n_sds(10)' 1 time
##     verb redux_fn        predicate       column index value
## 1 insist       NA within_n_sds(10) nPregnancies  3696    32
## 
## Column 'AlcoholDay' violates assertion 'within_n_sds(10)' 6 times
##     verb redux_fn        predicate     column index value
## 1 insist       NA within_n_sds(10) AlcoholDay  2839    36
## 2 insist       NA within_n_sds(10) AlcoholDay  2840    36
## 3 insist       NA within_n_sds(10) AlcoholDay  2841    36
## 4 insist       NA within_n_sds(10) AlcoholDay  5252    82
## 5 insist       NA within_n_sds(10) AlcoholDay  5540    64
##   [omitted 1 rows]
## 
## 
## Column 'SmokeAge' violates assertion 'within_n_sds(10)' 2 times
##     verb redux_fn        predicate   column index value
## 1 insist       NA within_n_sds(10) SmokeAge  2944    72
## 2 insist       NA within_n_sds(10) SmokeAge  9499    72
## Error: assertr stopped execution

This shows the instances of extreme outliers in our dataset.

"I chose to use within_n_sds in this example because people are familiar z-scores. However, for most practical purposes, the related predicate generator within_n_mads is more useful.

The problem with within_n_sds is the mean and standard deviation are so heavily influenced by outliers, their very presence will compromise attempts to identify them using these statistics. In contrast with within_n_sds, within_n_mads uses the robust statistics, median and median absolute deviation, to identify potentially erroneous data points.

For example, the vector <7.4, 7.1, 7.2, 72.1> almost certainly has an erroneous data point, but within_n_sds(2) will fail to detect it."

example <- c(7, 7.2, 7.9, 72.1)
within_n_sds(2)(example)(example)
## [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE
within_n_mads(2)(example)(example)
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE
within_n_mads(1)(example)(example)
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE
nh %>% 
  select_if(is.numeric) %>% 
  insist(within_n_mads(10), Age:DirectChol)
## Column 'Testosterone' violates assertion 'within_n_mads(10)' 190 times
##     verb redux_fn         predicate       column index  value
## 1 insist       NA within_n_mads(10) Testosterone  5003 642.82
## 2 insist       NA within_n_mads(10) Testosterone  5004 642.82
## 3 insist       NA within_n_mads(10) Testosterone  5020 763.00
## 4 insist       NA within_n_mads(10) Testosterone  5031 673.12
## 5 insist       NA within_n_mads(10) Testosterone  5043 642.09
##   [omitted 185 rows]
## Error: assertr stopped execution

More Complicated/Useful Assertions

"The problem having to plot data sets to catch anomalies is that it is really hard to visualize 4-dimensions at once, and it is near impossible with high-dimensional data.

There’s no way of catching this anomaly by looking at each individual column separately; the only way to catch it is to view each row as a complete observation and compare it to the rest.

To this end, assertr provides three functions that take a data frame, and reduce each row into a single value. We’ll call them row reduction functions.

The first one we’ll look at is called maha_dist. It computes the average mahalanobis distance (kind of like multivariate z-scoring for outlier detection) of each row from the whole data set. The big idea is that in the resultant vector, big/distant values are potential anomalous entries. Let’s look at the distribution of mahalanobis distances for this data set…"

nh_smaller <- nh %>% filter(Gender == "male") %>%  select(BMI, Testosterone, BPSysAve, BPDiaAve)

maha_dist(nh_smaller, keep.NA = FALSE) %>% head(n = 20)
##  [1] 2.7209968 2.7209968 2.7209968 3.0412581 5.3731002 4.5958436 0.3987988
##  [8] 1.9007806 1.6055360 2.3372410 0.2859758 6.5675230 0.2913898 9.7176401
## [15] 9.7176401 3.7096103 2.8172170 0.9943758 2.7223468 2.7223468
maha_dist(nh_smaller, keep.NA = FALSE) %>% hist(main = "", xlab = "")

"There’s no question here as to whether there’s an anomalous entry! But how do you check for this sort of thing using assertr constructs?

Well, maha_dist will typically be used with the insist_rows function. insist_rows takes a data frame, a row reduction function, a predicate-generating function, and an arbitrary number of columns to apply the predicate function to. The row reduction function (maha_dist in this case) is applied to the data frame, and returns a value for each row. The predicate-generating function is then applied to the vector returned from the row reduction function and the resultant predicate is applied to each element of that vector. It will raise an error if it finds any violations.

As always, this undoubtedly sounds far more confusing than it really is. Here’s an example of it in use"

nh_smaller %>% 
  insist_rows(maha_dist, within_n_mads(3), everything())
## Data frame row reduction 'maha_dist' violates predicate 'within_n_mads(3)' 167 times
##          verb  redux_fn        predicate        column index    value
## 1 insist_rows maha_dist within_n_mads(3) ~everything()  2477 10.61986
## 2 insist_rows maha_dist within_n_mads(3) ~everything()  2478 10.61986
## 3 insist_rows maha_dist within_n_mads(3) ~everything()  2511 10.35621
## 4 insist_rows maha_dist within_n_mads(3) ~everything()  2536 17.69782
## 5 insist_rows maha_dist within_n_mads(3) ~everything()  2543 11.91619
##   [omitted 162 rows]
## Error: assertr stopped execution

"Check that out! To be clear, this function is running the supplied data frame through the maha_dist function which returns a value for each row corresponding to its mahalanobis distance. (The whole data frame is used because we used the everything() selection function from the dplyr package.) Then, within_n_mads(3) computes on that vector and returns a bounds checking predicate. The bounds checking predicate checks to see that all mahalanobis distances are within 3 median absolute deviations of each other. They are not, and the pipeline errors out. Note that the data.frame of errors that is returned by error report contains the verb used (insist_rows), the row reduction function, the predicate, the column (or columns), the index of the failure and the offendind datum.

This is probably the most powerful construct in assertr–it can find a whole lot of nasty errors that would be very difficult to check for by hand.

Part of what makes it so powerful is how flexible maha_dist is. We only used it, so far, on a data frame of numerics, but it can handle all sorts of data frames. To really see it shine, let’s use it on the iris data set, that contains a categorical variable in its right-most column…"

"insist and insist_rows are both similar in that they both take predicate generators and not actual predicates. What makes insist_rows different is its usage of a row-reduce data frame.

assert has a row-oriented counterpart, too; it’s called assert_rows. insist is to assert as insist_rows is to assert_rows.

assert_rows works the same as insist_rows, except that instead of using a predicate generator on the row-reduced data frame, it uses a regular-old predicate.

For an example of a assert_rows use case, let’s say that we got a data set (another-dataset.csv) from the web and we don’t want to continue processing the data set if any row contains more than two missing values (NAs). You can use the row reduction function num_row_NAs to reduce all the rows into the number of NAs they contain. Then, a simple bounds checker will suffice for ensuring that no element is higher than 2…"

nh_smaller %>% 
    assert_rows(num_row_NAs, within_bounds(0,2), everything())
## Data frame row reduction 'num_row_NAs' violates predicate 'within_bounds(0, 2)' 631 times
##          verb    redux_fn           predicate        column index value
## 1 assert_rows num_row_NAs within_bounds(0, 2) ~everything()     4     3
## 2 assert_rows num_row_NAs within_bounds(0, 2) ~everything()    36     3
## 3 assert_rows num_row_NAs within_bounds(0, 2) ~everything()    37     4
## 4 assert_rows num_row_NAs within_bounds(0, 2) ~everything()    38     3
## 5 assert_rows num_row_NAs within_bounds(0, 2) ~everything()    51     3
##   [omitted 626 rows]
## Error: assertr stopped execution

assert_rows can be used for anomaly detection as well. A future version of assertr may contain a cosine distance row reduction function. Since all cosine distances are constained from -1 to 1, it is easy to use a non-dynamic predicate to disallow certain values.

Using success, error, and defect to change the behavior of assert, insist, and verify.

“The behavior of functions like assert, assert_rows, insist, insist_rows, verify when the assertion passes, fails or is skipped due to data defect is configurable via the success_fun, error_fun and defect_fun parameters, respectively.”

The success_fun parameter takes a function that takes the data passed to the assertion function as a parameter. You can write your own success handler function, but there are a few provided by this package:

  • success_continue - just returns the data that was passed into the assertion function (this is default).

  • success_logical - returns TRUE

  • success_append - returns the data that was passed into the assertion function but also attaches basic information about verification result to a special attribute of data.

  • success_report - when success results are stored (chain_start(store_results=TRUE)), and each verification ended up with success, it prints a summary of all successful validations (when being in chan) or simple verification result for single check and returns data.

  • success_df_return - when success results are stored (chain_start(store_results=TRUE)), and each verification ended up with success, it prints data.frame with verification results (can be used for chain_end or single verification).

## CHANGING THE RESULTS OF A SUCCESSFUL ASSERTION
nh %>% 
  mutate(Gender = as.character(Gender)) %>% 
  assert(char.4.6, Gender, success_fun = success_logical)
## [1] TRUE
nh %>% 
  mutate(Gender = as.character(Gender)) %>% 
  assert(char.4.6, Gender, success_fun = success_report)
## assert: verification [char.4.6] passed! Verified columns: Gender

The error_fun parameter takes a function that takes the data passed to the assertion function as a parameter. You can write your own error handler function, but there are a few provided by this package:

  • error_stop - Prints a summary of the errors and halts execution (default)

  • error_report - Prints all the information available about the errors and halts execution.

  • error_append - Attaches the errors to a special attribute of data and returns the data. This is chiefly to allow assertr errors to be accumulated in a pipeline so that all assertions can have a chance to be checked and so that all the errors can be displayed at the end of the chain.

  • error_logical - returns FALSE

  • just_warn - Prints a summary of the errors but does not halt execution, it just issues a warning.

  • warn_report - Prints all the information available about the errors but does not halt execution, it just issues a warning.

  • defect_report - For single rule and defective data it displays short info about skipping the current assertion. For chain_end sums up all skipped rules for defective data.

  • defect_df_return - For single rule and defective data it returns info data.frame about skipping current assertion. For chain_end returns all skipped rules info data.frame for defective data.

## Error: assertr stopped execution

The defect_fun parameter takes a function that takes the data passed to the assertion function as a parameter. Defect handler is called when any of previous assertions that was marked as obligatory failed (see below section). You can write your own defect handler function, but there are a few provided by this package:

  • defect_append - Attaches the assertion call info on defective data to a special attribute of data and returns the data.

  • defect_report - For single rule and defective data it displays short info about skipping current assertion. For chain_end sums up all skipped rules for defective data.

  • defect_df_return - For single rule and defective data it returns info data.frame about skipping current assertion. For chain_end returns all skipped rules info data.frame for defective data.

nh %>% 
  mutate(Race1 = as.character(Race1)) %>% 
  assert(function(x) (nchar(x) == 4 | nchar(x) == 6), Race1, error_fun = defect_report)
## Error in defect_append(errors, data, ...): the ... list contains fewer than 1 element

Combining Assertions

When you run a series of assert steps, when one hits an error, it will stop running the code. However, you can use a special function to run through all of the assertion steps before erroring out. This is done using the chain_start and chain_end functions.

nh %>% 
    assert(not_na, Testosterone) %>%  ## Will Stop here
    assert(within_bounds(0, 60), Age) %>% 
    assert(in_set(c("No", "Yes")), SmokeNow, HardDrugs) %>% 
    assert(is_uniq, ID) %>% 

nh %>% 
  chain_start %>% 
    assert(not_na, Testosterone) %>%
    assert(within_bounds(0, 60), Age) %>% 
    assert(in_set(c("No", "Yes")), SmokeNow, HardDrugs) %>% 
    assert(is_uniq, ID) %>% 
  chain_end
## Error in nh(.): could not find function "nh"

Let’s try and abstractify this portion so we can run it often.

check_me <- . %>%
  chain_start %>%
    verify(nrow(nh_smaller) > 5000) %>%
    verify(BMI > 0) %>%
    insist(within_n_sds(4), BPSysAve) %>%
    assert(not_na, Testosterone) %>% 
  chain_end

check_me

##  5. assert(., not_na, Testosterone)
##  6. chain_end(.)

nh_smaller %>%
